    <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
    <div id="main_content_wrap" class="outer">
      	<section id="main_content" class="inner">

    	<p>
		A little example of Kiabora's capabilities.
		</p>

        <h2>Input file:</h2>
			<pre>p(X,Z) :- p(X,Y), p(Y,Z).
p(Y,X), q(X,Y,X) :- p(X,Y).
q(X,Z,T) :- r(X,Y).
r(Z,T) :- q(X,Y,Z).
s(Z,Z,Z) :- p(X,X), r(Y,U), s(T,Y,X).
s(Z,X,Y) :- s(X,X,X), s(Y,Y,Y).</pre>

			<h2>Output (all options turned on): </h2>

<p>The '-r' option can be used to display the rule set.</p>
			<pre>
====== RULE SET ======
[R0] p(X, Z) :- p(X, Y), p(Y, Z).
[R1] p(Y, X), q(X, Y, X) :- p(X, Y).
[R2] q(X, Z, T) :- r(X, Y).
[R3] r(Z, T) :- q(X, Y, Z).
[R4] s(Z, Z, Z) :- p(X, X), r(Y, U), s(T, Y, X).
[R5] s(Z, X, Y) :- s(X, X, X), s(Y, Y, Y).
</pre>

<p>The '-g' option can be used to display the graph of rule dependencies.
Here the '-u' option has been used, thus, unifiers also appear.</p>
<pre>
======== GRD =========
R0--{R::Y->D::Z,R::X->D::X}{R::Y->D::X,R::Z->D::Z}-->R0
R0--{R::Y->D::Z,R::X->D::X}-->R1
R0--{R::X->D::Z,D::X->D::Z}-->R4
R1--{R::Y->D::X,R::X->D::Y}{R::Y->D::Y,R::Z->D::X}-->R0
R1--{R::Y->D::X,R::X->D::Y}-->R1
R1--{D::Y->D::X,R::X->D::X}-->R4
R1--{R::Y->D::Y,R::Z->D::X,R::X->D::X}-->R3
R2--{R::Y->D::Z,R::Z->D::T,R::X->D::X}-->R3
R3--{R::Y->D::T,R::X->D::Z}-->R2
R3--{R::Y->D::Z,R::U->D::T}-->R4
R4--{R::X->D::Z}{R::Y->D::Z}-->R5
R5--{R::T->D::Z,R::Y->D::X,R::X->D::Y}-->R4
</pre>

<p>With the '-s' option, Kiabora displays the strongly connected component of the
graph of rule dependencies.
<pre>
======== SCC =========
C0 = {R1, R0}
C1 = {R2, R3}
C2 = {R4, R5}
</pre>


<p>
And with '-G', Kiabora also displays the graph
of the SCC.
</p>
<pre>
===== SCC GRAPH ======
C0 ---> C1, C2
C1 ---> C2
C2
</pre>

<p>
Rule properties are printed for each rule,
thanks to the '-P' switch.
</p>
<pre>
== RULE PROPERTIES ===
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|  -   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  ?   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  R0  
|  -   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  R1  
|  X   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  R2  
|  X   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  R3  
|  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  R4  
|  X   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  R5  
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| aGRD | bts  | disc |  dr  | fes  |  fg  | fr1  | fus  | gbts | lin  |  rr  |  s   |  wa  | wfg  |  wg  |  ws  |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
</pre>

<p>Then, the rule set properties are checked against the full rule set (-R).</p>
<pre>
===== PROPERTIES =====
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|  -   |  ?   |  -   |  -   |  ?   |  -   |  -   |  ?   |  ?   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| aGRD | bts  | disc |  dr  | fes  |  fg  | fr1  | fus  | gbts | lin  |  rr  |  s   |  wa  | wfg  |  wg  |  ws  |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
</pre>

<p>
And the SCC properties can also be displayed (used for the combine steps) with -S.
</p>
<pre>
=== SCC PROPERTIES ===
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|  -   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  ?   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  C0  
|  -   |  X   |  -   |  -   |  ?   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  -   |  X   |  X   |  X   |  C1  
|  -   |  ?   |  -   |  X   |  ?   |  -   |  -   |  X   |  ?   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  -   |  C2  
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| aGRD | bts  | disc |  dr  | fes  |  fg  | fr1  | fus  | gbts | lin  |  rr  |  s   |  wa  | wfg  |  wg  |  ws  |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
</pre>

<p>Finally, Kiabora tries to find some combined approach for finite reasoning.
First by maximising the number of components to be treated in forward chaining, then by
maximising the backward chaining.
Note that in this example, no property ensuring
decidability have been found on the whole rule
set, however, by using some combined approach,
we can ensure a finite time reasoning.
</p>
<pre>
=== COMBINE (FES) ====
C0: FES
C1: FUS
C2: FUS


=== COMBINE (FUS) ====
C0: FES
C1: FUS
C2: FUS
</pre>
